column169: The driver stopped at a truck stop in Knoxville, TN on 4/10/2024 around 1140. Upon exiting the truck, the driver noticed there was material leaking from the front of the trailer, onto the front, right tractor tire. The driver called Superior's Regulatory Department. Superior's Regulatory Department called a spill contractor. The spill response contractor arrived and began cleanup efforts. The spill contractor removed most of the drums from the trailer, found the leaking drum (55 gallon steel drum), and then overpacked the leaking drum.  Once the leaking drum was overpacked, they cleaned the inside of the trailer.  Once the trailer was clean, they reloaded all of the drums back into the trailer. the total amount of material spilled in the trailer was approximately 79 lbs. The only cost incurred will be from the spill contractor. However, we do not have the final bill back yet from the spill contractor.

column169: On April 26th, 2024, at 05:57 hours, personnel in the CSX Gentilly Yard reported a derailment involving loaded tank cars of NA1993, Fuel Oil, Combustible Liquid, PGIII.  One of the five derailed tank cars, NATX 301139, was on its side and found to be leaking from the Vacuum Relief Valve.  All other derailed cars were found to be leak free.  SPSI, a CSX response contractor, and two CSX Managers of Hazardous Materials, responded the incident.  Response personnel partially plugged and fully contained the release upon arrival.  Once the car was rerailed to an upright the position, the release was stopped.  CSX subsequently transloaded, cleaned and purged this car in preparation for the car being dismantled onsite for scrap; repair costs exceeded the value of the car.

SequenceEvent: During inspection it was noted that the four gallons were put inside a plastic bag and tied with a zip tie.  The gallons were not actively leaking but there was a strong smell and the inside of the bag was damp. Two of the gallons looked like they had lost fluid. DescribePack: The box was wet.  The inside of the bag was wet.  I am unsure where the leak came from DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The package was placed inside a plastic lined tote and put in the hazmat cage.

A FULLY LABELED HAZMAT PACKAGE THAT APPEARED TO BE LEAKING WAS DISCOVERED BY A LOADER ON THE PD 11. THE LOADER LEFT THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR. WITHIN 5 MINUTES A DMP RESPONDER ARRIVED DONNING THE CORRECT PPE AND USING THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE PACKAGE COULD BE SAFELY TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE DMP. UPON FURTHER INSPECTION IT WAS REVEALED THAT THE CAPS ON TWO OF THE INNER PLASTIC CONTAINERS WERE LOOSE BY 1/4 OF A TURN AND TWO OUNCES OF LIQUID LEAKED OUT ONTO THE OUTER CARTON. THERE WAS NO PACKING MATERIAL AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A SINGLE WALLED FIBERBOARD BOX

column169: XPO-Logistics contacted ERTS regarding (24) punctured or impacted 2.5-gallon jugs of Brimstone that resulted in  approximately 2-gallons of product releasing onto the wooden trailer floor and the concrete dock floor. The  dock floor was impacted in a 2’x3’ area and the trailer floor was impacted in a 2’x8’ area. A Contractor  cleaned-up the released product and neutralized the impacted areas with soda ash. The damaged product, spill  debris, and PPE were containerized for waste disposal in four 55-gallon poly drums. No storm-drains,  waterways, or soil were affected by this incident.

column169: X-2024051203: H-BELPHX1-25A derailed containing six Propane cars that were involved in fire due to container breaches/damage. NATX 400688 suffered jacket damage and some dents. The car suffered a 19"x2" heat-induced tear on the "B-end". This car was turned over in a pit and burned itself out after consuming all remaining propane liquid.  X-2024051204: H-BELPHX1-25A derailed containing six Propane cars that were involved in fire due to container breaches/damage. UTLX 952565 suffered jacket damage and some dents. After being exposed to flame impingement for hours, the tank suffered what appears to be a heat-induced tear measuring about 6"x1" on the top of the tank, underneath the jacket. The tank also had a significant blister at this point as well. Significant heat damage to protective housing as well. This car was turned over in a pit and burned itself out after consuming all remaining propane liquid.  X-2024051207: H-BELPHX1-25A derailed containing six Propane cars that were involved in fire due to container breaches/damage. UTLX 955642 suffered jacket damage and some dents. The tank suffered a puncture/tear toward the A-end of the car measuring about 2'x3'. This car was turned over in a pit and burned itself out after consuming all remaining propane liquid.  X-2024051208: H-BELPHX1-25A derailed containing six Propane cars that were involved in fire due to container breaches/damage. UTLX 954193 suffered jacket damage and some dents on each end, but no container failure. After being exposed to flame impingement for hours, all gaskets/o-rings were burnt out from valves under the protective housing and product burned from these orifices. The protective housing also had significant damage. This car had burned itself out after consuming all remaining propane liquid.  X-2024051209: H-BELPHX1-25A derailed containing six Propane cars that were involved in fire due to container breaches/damage. UTLX 959911 suffered jacket damage and some dents including a significant B-end head dent, but no container failure. After being exposed to flame impingement for hours, all gaskets/o-rings were burnt out from valves under the protective housing and product burned from these orifices. This car was turned over in a pit and burned itself out after consuming all remaining propane liquid.  X-2024051210: H-BELPHX1-25A derailed containing six Propane cars that were involved in fire due to container breaches/damage. UTLX 953969 suffered jacket damage and some dents including a dent on each end, but no container failure. This car did have multiple PRD venting cycles due to being exposed to heat/fire for hours. This car was liquid flared and then vapor flared to remove all remaining product.

THE SPILL HAD BEEN COVERED WITH ABSORBANT PADS AND THE METAL PAIL HAD BEEN COVERED AND MOVED OUT OF REACH OF OTHER EMPLOYEES. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: THE METAL PAIL WAS PUT INSIDE A PLASTIC BAG, STANDING UPRIGHT AND COVERED SO THAT THE PAINT FUMES WOULD NOT ESCAPE.

QA was told that the driver had the package on their truck from the previous day and that when he opened up his side door the package fell out of his truck and onto the ground. Neutralizer was put onto the spill until it came up as non-acidic. Loose particulate was then placed on the spill area to absorb the liquid. DescribePack: The cap was loose on one of the jugs. The cap fell off after the package fell out of the drivers truck. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Neutralizer was used to negate the acid in the liquid. Loose particulate was placed on the spill.

column169: On 4/2/2024, at 1624 hours, FRA Hazardous Materials Inspector L. Rawls, at the CSXT Gentilly Yard in New Orleans, LA discovered UTLX 130322, a residue tank car last contained: Zinc Chloride, with the fill port cover open. The car was isolated and the shipper, Micronutrients, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report 2024-04-02--00252).   Specialized Professional Services, Inc. (SPSI), a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to assess and correct the reported issue. SPSI personnel inspected, closed and secured the fill port cover.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative (Keith Hughes at 317-494-0256).  While no visible product release was noted, because this shipment was found open to the atmosphere, and per FRA guidance, it is presumed that some volume of hazardous material vapor or residue was released.

R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to remediate the impacted site. All sodium hydroxide-impacted materials were containerized in one (1) additional 55-gallon drum for disposal.

column170: Although it is unclear what caused the hole in the drum, it is important to ensure that the customer is using proper packaging and handling procedures for shipping containers before offering the waste to Veolia. Also, Veolia employees must do thorough inspections on all containers to ensure that container integrity is not compromised in any way at the time of pick up from the customer.

column169: On April 4, 2024, one (1) 275-gallon tote of corrosive liquid was punctured by a forklift and released approximately 115-gallons of product to the trailer interior and pavement beneath. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to remediate the impacted site. HCE personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted roadway/trailer interior and swept them in with hand tools. HCE utilized an additional tote to complete a gravity feed from the impacted 275-gallon tote. All spent absorbents, absorbent pads and collected waste were collected and containerized into six (6) 55-gallon metal drums and PPE was containerized into a separate 55-gallon open top poly drum. All were labeled and set aside for terminal disposal.

At about 17:30, a woman called RTS stating that she was following a tanker pulled by an RTS truck on RT 83 and residual material from the tanker had splashed onto her car (a red crossover Mercedes-Benz).  RTS was transporting a tanker from American Woodmark Corp. and had dropped the tanker in its transfer line. Records indicate the driver had noted a faulty seal at the top of the tanker on his post trip inspection. Investigation confirmed that the grey material that had splashed down the side of the tanker, as well as on the ground from the manhole overflow tube appeared similar to the specks splashed on the car.   No material was on the roadway. The spill in the transfer line was cleaned up, and a reportable spill report filed. The citizen arrived on site to show us the material on her car, which were small droplets of grey material.  The gasket/seal has been replaced.
column170: The gasket/seal has been replaced.  RTS is evaluating a preventative gasket/seal replacement program.

column169: SequenceEvent: The box was unloaded off the trailer. Then the box was transported to the van that was to deliver the box. An hour later, the driver of the van saw the box was leaking white small granules. The driver called a manager who came over to the van with gloves, broom, dustpan and a red hazmat plastic container. The manager put the box inside the red hazmat plastic container and swept up any granules that came out of the box. He then gently put the granules inside the box. The box was then transported to the hazmat cage by the Ops Admin. DescribePack: The bottom of the plastic bucket had a dent on the corner. The dent was about 3" long.  The bottom of the plastic bucket has a crack going along the outside seem about 8 inches long. Upon inspection saw underneath this plastic bottom was another plastic bottom. This inside plastic bottom was cracked in several places. The cracks ranged from 7 inches to 3 inches. I could see the product had leaked out of these cracks and the very outside crack. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The box was turned upside down and placed inside a red plastic hazmat container. The leakage of the product stopped since the cracks were on the bottom of the plastic bucket that was inside the box.

column169: On April 16, 2024, at 19:33, Tank Car IAPX 1141 was observed, during a roll-by inspection, as actively emitting vapor from the top discharge stack.  Upon investigation, the vapor valve handle located in the A-R cabinet was found to be slightly opened, with secondary closure turnbuckles and zip ties broken loose from the valve handle.  The valve was closed and spare turnbuckles and zip ties (found in the cabinet) were re-applied to the valve for secondary securement.  Estimated duration of the release was undeterminable, the vapor valve and associated piping was found frosted.
column170: Use of better packaging, especially focused on something more secure than zip-ties and turnbuckles for secondary closure securement should be required.

column59: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column169: At 0140 on 4/12/24 it was reported that empty Ammonia Solution car GATX 71080 was making a venting/hissing noise while in the CPKC Mossville rail yard. CPKC Hazmat mobilized a railroad qualified response contractor to investigate and mitigate the release. Upon arrival, responders determined the tank car had 80psi of pressure within. Further inspection revealed that the Kelso re-closing pressure relief device(PRD), with a setting of 165psi, was the source of the leak and could not be repaired in the field. The pressure on the tank car was reduced by sparging the vapors through water to scrub the ammonia vapors until Opsi in GATX 71080 was met. Wet towels were placed around the PRD and a plastic bag was used around the towels to absorb any Ammonia vapors that might have been released. The car was subsequently purged and cleaned, and the shipper procured an OTMA-1 to move the car to home shop for repairs. File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at the time of filing. This shipment was offered as a'bulk' shipment, aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered in this package is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantify this value.
column170: The Kansas City Southern Railway(KCSR)(DBA CPKC) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases(NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases(a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCSR.(Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Carl Akins, KCSR Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar. com for help understanding and preventing NARs. r (NAR: 702)

column169: • Our driver was doing a pump unload.  They unloaded 3838 gallons before one of her hoses developed a hole (towards the end – about 6-12” from the hose fitting) and was spraying the side of her truck and the ground.   • She shut down right away but by the time pressure worked off of the hoses 10-15 gallons spilled out on the ground (gravel and grass).  The customer handled clean up.   • Turns out her hose was past the 1 year inspection interval we require on the hoses.  An inspection of the hose showed no obvious signs of deterioration and appear to be age related
column170: Driver was brought in for safety training and to evaluate all of her hoses for valid inspections.  This was our hazmat fleet message this week to all drivers ensuring they are checking their hose inspection dates.

column169: An East Penn Logistics, LLC driver was on Cypress Road Maryland, Rt 291, heading towards the Maryland / Delaware line. While checking in his mirrors he drifted right, went off the road into a ditch and tried to recover back onto the road and over corrected and ended in a roll over onto the driver's side. The driver was treated for minor injuries.  The local Police responded to the scene. They called a local towing company to assist in the clean up and the towing of the truck. The Maryland Department of Environment also responded to the call. By the time they arrived, the incident was mostly cleaned up. They were happy with the clean up and no further action to be done via the MD EPA for clean up. The truck and batteries were towed back to Phillips Garage in Sudlersville, MD. The driver returned the next day to help repalletize and package the scrap batteries for shipping back to East Penn Manufacturing, Lyons Station for proper disposal of the batteries at our secondary lead smelter.

On April 17, 2024, two (2) 55-gallon drums of acetone were damaged due to a pallet failure in transit. Due to the damage, the drums released approximately ten (10) gallons of acetone to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site. TLE personnel collected two (2) damaged drums and placed them in 85-gallon overpack for potential reuse. Crews then deployed granular absorbent to the impacted trailer floor and worked them in utilizing hand tools. Once collected, TLE personnel utilized a degreasing agent and absorbent pads to collect any residual product. All acetone impacted material was collected and containerized into one (1) 15-gallon drum and RLC personnel took possession of all three (3) drums to be added to the facility waste stream.

column169: Hepaco was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted an 8ft-by-50ft area of the trailer floor and a 25ft-by-100ft area of the concrete lot and estimated that seventy-five (75) gallons of material was released from one (1) 275-gallon poly tote. Hepaco personnel deployed a granular absorbent and a neutralizer to the impacted areas. The spent material was gathered and containerized into eight (8) 55-gallon poly drums. The generated waste was transported to the local Dayton Freight terminal and placed in a secure location for the terminal to coordinate disposal. The generated waste will remain onsite for the Dayton Freight team to coordinate disposal.

DescribePack: upon discovery the outer box had a wet spot on it like it had been dripped down internally. At the time I did not know it was a hazmat as the outer box did not have any markings on it to indicate that it was a hazmat. The inner box had a large wet spot on the top and partially down both sides of the inner box. Other than that there wasnt any other kind of damage to the outer or inner box. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Once I discovered it was a hazmat I had to run to the sink and thoroughly wash my hands as I had touched the wet part of the box. When I returned I put on nitrile gloves, grabbed a hazmat bag, and put the damaged package into a red lined bin. I then used some absorbent pads to soak up and wipe down the surface area where the box had been located.

column169: The material was picked up at the shipper's location in the morning. There was no evidence of a leak at that time. At the 2nd stop of the day, there was an odor in the back of the truck but no observable liquid. The truck returned to the transporter facility and at that point, there was some visible liquid on the container, but no liquid on the floor of the truck. Leaked amount was less than 1 liter.  A new gasket was procured, and when the lid was removed to replace the gasket, it was observed that the original gasket had a small section that was not fully seated around the edge. The used gasket was removed and a new one was correctly installed. The shipment continued without further issue.
column170: Team members were informed of the incident and will be double checking the gasket seating in the future.

Enviroserve was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 2in-by-15ft area of the trailer  floor  and  10ft-by-5ft  area  of  the  concrete  terminal  dock  and  estimated  that  one  (1)  gallon  of material  was  released  due  to  a  damaged  55-gallon  poly  drum.  Enviroserve  personnel  deployed granular absorbents to the impacted areas and used absorbent pads to gather the spent material. The recovered absorbents were placed into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The damaged drum was emptied into two (2) 30-gallon poly drums and the damaged 55-gallon was over-packed into one (1) 85-gallon poly  drum.  The  generated  waste  was  staged  onsite  at  the  terminal  in  a  secure  location  prior  to  the contractor  demobilization.  The  generated  waste  will  remain  onsite  for  the  ESTES  DGRM  team  to coordinate disposal.

XPO-XTM contacted ERTS regarding a punctured leaking tote containing Predator MR2516. The tote was  punctured by a forklift and released approximately 35-gallons of product onto the wooden trailer floor and  concrete underneath the trailer. The trailer floor impact area was 18'x18' and the impact area underneath the  trailer was 8'x20'. A Contractor performed a tote transfer, cut-up pallets that were impacted by the release, and  cleaned-up the release on the trailer floor. Five drums of waste were generated for disposal. No storm-drains,  waterways, or soil were affected by this incident.

column169: Lone Star Hazmat Response was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 6ft-by-1ft area of the trailer floor and estimated that one (1) quart of material was released due improper loading of  the  freight  that  resulted  in  one  (1)  15-gallon  plastic  jug  to  overturn  and  leak. SequenceEvent: Package came off of truck in Unload notably wet, was placed into lined tote immediately and moved to safe area. Unable to determine if this occurred when initially loaded to trailer or during transit to our station. Upon opening outer packaging found one of four 4L bottles of water (non-hazardous) had somehow broken during shipping causing water to release inside package and eventually seep out as well. DescribePack: There were corrugated moldings around each of the four bottles to help protect during shipping but evidently was not enough to keep one bottle from getting broken. When that happened water leaked out inside, compromising structural integrity of inner, outer packaging and causing the box/moldings to tear and distort due to weight of 3 non-broken bottles. Bottle was already broken coming off of trailer so no knowledge of what directly caused damage to occur. DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: Water had already leaked out due to bottle being broken completely. Cleaned up all wet areas in trailer and unload to re-establish safe working environment. Thankfully as stated through this report, the box was labeled as a Hazmat but did not contain any hazardous contents. Not sure if it was a mix-up by shipper when assigning labels to packages or what cause was, but no hazardous contents were in package or leaked out.

On April 11th, a package was observed to have smoke coming out of it during the sort. The package was removed to the outside of the facility in case a full fire erupted. Emergency services were not called to examine the package. Shortly after the smoke lessened and the box was no longer hot to the touch. The package was brought in and examined and it was determined that there were four non-spillable batteries inside, two of which showed scorch marks from a small fire. The package was placed into a steel salvage drum and is being help pending disposition. The NRC was notified of the fire at approximately 2300, report # 1396190.

XPO Logistics contacted ERTS regarding a roadside release of Kurifloc 7115 from a 275-gallon tote as a result of  improper loading / inadequate preparation for transportation. The tote became crushed under falling freight  breaking the cap and causing the release during transit. Approximately 10-gallons of product released onto the  trailer floor, the asphalt beneath the trailer, and the concrete parking lot. The impact areas include the trailer  floor: 4'x4', asphalt beneath the trailer: 2'x8', and concrete parking lot: 3'x20'. A Contractor secured the freight for the trailer to pull into a parking lot where a tote transfer was performed and the trailer floor was neutralized  with white vinegar. The transferred tote was loaded onto trailer while the damaged tote was taken by the  Contractor to XPO’s Shreveport, LA terminal to be cut-up and containerized for waste disposal. Additionally,  one drum containing PPE, impacted oil dry, and impacted absorbent rags was generated for waste disposal. No  storm-drains, soil, or waterways were impacted by this incident.

column169: Driver stopped at the end of the day and noticed liquid in his trailer while doing his post trip. The driver then notified  our emergency response center at approximately 2300CT. The response team was dispatched to the sight arriving around 0200ct. They then dawned the appropriate PPE and began unloading the trailer to reach the container that was leaking. They found that the securement strap where it was secured to the wall of the trailer had rubbed a hole in the chime of the drum. The team then proceeded to place the damaged drum into a salvage drum and collected the released material with absorbents and then disposed of in the appropriate manner. The clean up was completed at 0800ct.
column170: Placement of securement straps and where they are attached to the trailer needs to be done so that they will not rub the container.

column169: The release occurred due to the intermodal container tipping on its side while in the STG Logistics yard, due to heavy weight at top of container. As a result, a minimal amount of product released from the seal on the tipped totes. Free product was contained to gravel surface just below the intermodal container. Container was up righted, and Ambipar was dispatched to perform the cleanup. Upon arrival on site, Ambipar inspected the container and confirmed totes were in tact, a minimal amount of free product had released from the seal, and was contained to container surface and gravel. Ambipar proceeded to use absorbent material to absorb the free product, and surface scraped the impacted gravel from within the lot. Freight was offloaded, container was cleaned, and shipment was reloaded and secured. Two 55-gallon drums of spent absorbent, cleanup debris, and impacted gravel were generated.
column170: STG Logistics will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column169: On 4-29-2024 a CN transportation employee observed liquid dripping from the bottom outlet valve, loading equipment was observed to still be attached with the cap dangling during routing work operations at the CN Sioux City Yard in Sioux City, IA. The employee initiated an emergency response from the CN Dangerous Goods Team. The tank car has been set out on an isolation track (SC98) The transportation Employee placed a bucket underneath the rail car to contain the leak.   A CN emergency response contractor was dispatched to the location for mitigation. The CN contractor found loading equipment was still attached and the cap was not attached but dangling by the chain. The attached loading valve was less than tool tight leaking from the threads.  The BOV valve handle was cycled several times to the open and closed position to free any debris that may have been trapped in the BOV sealing surface potentially causing the leak. The loading equipment valve was removed from the car and the bov valve was observed for 20 minutes to ensure there was no further leakage from the valve. The bottom outlet valve cap gasket was inspected and replaced. The BOV cap was then re-installed and tightened with a 36" pipe wrench.

On 4/17/2024 at approximately 2030, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 768735 at the ramp facility in Atlanta, reporting a flammable liquid spill.  The shipment consisted of two plastic jerricans, packaged inside of a fiberboard box, then overpacked in a larger fiberboard box.  One of the jerricans appeared to spill due to a damaged closure.  Further inspection revealed that the shipment was not properly declared as a dangerous goods shipment.  The inner fiberboard was UN-rated and marked with hazard class 3 label, however, the outer packaging had no such marking or labeling, nor did the shipment have the proper documentation.  An online safety data sheet classified the commodity as a combustible liquid via highway transport; however, the flash point would classify it as a fully regulated flammable liquid air IATA.  The shipment is being held, pending further investigation by the FAA.

column169: SequenceEvent: Package had been unloaded and was on van line ready to be loaded on van when the loading package handler saw that the box was wet. Package was set aside on a spill containment pallet, then placed in a lined container shortly after. DescribePack: 2 of the 4 jugs were packed in the box upside down, with the caps in contact with the bottom of the box. This allowed stress to be applied to caps, leading to them beginning to leak inside the plastic bags. The plastic bags then also began leaking, soiling the box and other contents. The caps had some tape wrapped around them, but this appears to have been ineffective at prevent leakage. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The external box contained mostly all of the spillage, becoming wet in the process. There was no visible wetness on conveyor belt, and only a slightly damp spot of the spill pallet. Spill neutralizer was applied to the spot. Package was placed in a lined container during inspection and reporting. During this, contents began to leak more due to manipulation. All leakage was contained by liner.

At 1121 Hrs. on 4-21-2024, the WLE Rook Yard Conductor found tank car NATX 318056 leaking from the manway on top the car.  He called the WLE Yardmaster who then contacted myself, John Vergis, Hazardous Materials Officer for the WLE.  I called Specialized Professional Services out of Washington, PA to go look at the car.  They determined that the manway was indeed leaking.  The found that the bolts were tight.  They opened the lid and found that the seal looked new and that there was not any compression markings at the point of the manway safety bolts.  They felt that the safety bolts did not have enough threads on them to tighten to the point that the gasket would compress.  The installed a nozzle gasket, to replace the ring gasket, and then was able to get the lid to tighten fully.  I had suggested to them that maybe the manway lid was improperly positioned on the nozzle causing the metal of the lid to hit the metal of the nozzle, thereby not letting the lid close tightly.  They said they did not check for that and therefore could not confirm that idea.  They closed the lid, tightened the bolts and installed new seal # 8418988 on the manway lid.  They had also checked for leaks in the Roll Over Protection Housing but found none and then installed new seal 8418983 on that lid.  The car was then released for service and after the car was moved, there was no leak noticed.

On April 26, 2024, one (1) 275-gallon tote of UN3265 was damaged by improper stacking and released approximately four (4) ounces of product to the dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Lone Star Hazmat (LSH) to remediate the impacted site. LSH personnel deployed neutralizers to the dock floor and exterior of the tote and utilized hand tools and absorbent pads to remediate the impacted surfaces. LSH patched the one (1) 275-gallon tote, placed absorbent pads beneath the tote and wrapped the tote in a poly sheet. Crews appropriately labeled and staged the poly sheet wrapped 275-gallon tote onsite. All spent absorbent pads and generated waste were collected and containerized into one (1) 5-gallon plastic pail for disposal.

column169: On 4/04/2024 Veolia employees were unloading a cubic yard box into a trailer at the 10-Day transfer area in Veolia, South Windsor, CT facility when an employee noticed a few drops of liquid coming out of a cubic yard box. Only a couple of drops were observed under the cubic yard box. The employees noticed the leak right away and quickly put down some spill pads to contain the leak. Employees proceeded to open the container and observed many inner paint related material containers were dented or leaking inside the cubic yard box. Employees righted the inner containers, poured absorbent into the cubic yard box to prevent any further leaks, and transported the container to the ultimate disposal facility.
column170: On 4/04/2024 the Veolia EH&S manager was notified of the incident. The EH&S manager investigated the incident and discovered that the shipper dropped the cubic yard box from an elevated height when preparing it for shipment. Human error did have a role in this incident. Veolia notified the shipper and requested that if a similar incident occurs in the future to please inspect the containers or notify Veolia at the time the container is being picked up for transportation. If a box is dropped in the future, the container will be inspected and the inner containers will be verified that they are not leaking. If any leaks are discovered, the container should be changed or the inner containers uprighted to prevent them from leaking.

column169: A third party hauler was hooking onto a Veolia's outbound trailer. When the trailer made contact with the king pin, a yellow liquid began to drop slowly out of the trailer, just behind the tractor. The driver was instructed to pull away from the van. A Veolia employee then went to grab a bag of solid absorb and placed it below the leak. Approximately 4oz of the liquid was spilled onto the cement floor before it stopped.   The trailer was then unloaded. During this time, the employees noticed that 3 drums were leaking from their bottom and sides. The bottom of the drums were corroded which caused pinholes on the bottom portion of the body of the drums. Employees then overpacked the 3 drums into poly containers. Approximately 4 oz of the liquid was released onto the trailer's floor.   These 3 drums were profiled as a solid by the vendor. Possible misclassification of the waste along with improper packaging may have caused the leak. All three drums were placed into a poly 85 salvage drum. The manifest was then rejected back to the broker, and the broker came back to pick up their drums.
column170: Veolia has communicated our findings to the initial transporter of this waste in which they will reach out to the original shipper to place necessary corrective actions in place. Part of the corrective action is that the waste must be accurately profiled and packaged in compatible packaging and this will not be accepted until they have provided their corrective actions to mitigate future occurrences.

He called the our emergency response team and they were dispatched to address the issue. The team arrived on sight at 2230. The then dawned the proper PPE and entered the trailer gaining access to the container that was leaking. There was a small pinhole in drum and the drum was placed into a Salvage drum. The material was then collected with absorbents and the disposed of in the appropriate manner. The clean up was completed around 0300ct.

PPRX 663916 was found in the BNSF Railway Hogkins yard leaking from the top of the car when the car was moved.  Upon inspection, it was determined that PPRX 663916 was leaking from the manway and released approximately 1 gallon of product.  A BNSF contractor was dispatched, inspected the car and found the  manway gasket deteriorated and one of 6 manway swing bolts less than tool tight.  The contractor installed a new manway gasket, properly secured the car and BNSF released it to destination.

The image on Spidr indicates the package was originally larger and totaling 49.00pounds and only had a label indicating it was fragile. One of the three containers conaining cyco platinum ph up had significant volumn missing due to a loose cap that was leaking when the container was flipped upside down. DurationRel: 4 and MitigateEffect: The package was placed in a hazmat tote once it was  discovered that it was hazardous. Proper PPE was donned, and the processing of a damaged hazmat was initiated.

column59: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column169: On April 13, 2024 at approximately 22:30 CDT during switching operations on the south end of the CN Geismar Yard, a CN transportation crew member observed vapors emitting from the top of tank car RCRX 2718 (Load / Hydrochloric Acid / UN 1789 / PG II / UN 1789). The CN Dangerous Goods Officer was notified of the incident and responded to the rail yard to investigate. The DGO inspection revealed a small amount of liquid pooled in the bowl of the external spring safety relief valve. The liquid was emitting vapors and tested as 1-2 PH indicating the liquid was corrosive coinciding with the lading. All service equipment fittings and closures were found to be properly secured. The product pooled in the bowl of the SRV was absorbed with a chemical pad. The SRV was bubble leak tested externally and was found to be leak free. The shipper of record was notified of the incident. A qualified mobile repair unit will replace the SRV on-site and re-qualify the tank car prior to continuing in transportation. The removed SRV will be sent to the manufacturer for a bench test.

column43: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column169: On 4/3/2024, at 16:54 hours, personnel in the CSXT Montgomery, AL Yard discovered TJRX 30025, a residue tank car that last contained Petroleum Distillates, NOS leaking from the bottom of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Gardner Asphalt, was notified via CHEMTREC (report 1395529). Marion Environmental, Inc. (MEI), a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and product leaking from the bottom outlet valve (BOV) with the valve in the closed position. MEI personnel actuated the valve between closed and open positions multiple times; once the valve was fully reclosed the release stopped.  Upon further inspection, it was noted that the gasket in the bottom outlet valve cap was worn.  Additionally, pieced of debris and corrosion were observed in the cap.  It is suspected that corrosion and debris present in the valve seat were the cause for product flow through the valve in the closed position.  Response personnel installed a new BOV cap gasket and secured the car for transportation.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative (Duane Thomas, 443-875-4818).

column169: XPO Logistics terminal XCW experienced a release from (4) 275-gallon poly totes. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 20-gallons of UN2734 Tri-Act 1800 released from (2) 275-gallon poly totes due to forklift punctures. Approximately 20-gallons of UN2920 Tri-Act 1820 also released from (2) 275-gallon poly totes due to a bent metal cage and a forklift puncture. The products collectively impacted a 6’ x 1’ area of the trailer floor, 20’ x 8’ area of the concrete lot, and a 40’ x 15’ & 10’ x 3’ areas of the concrete dock floor. All 4 totes of material were transferred into new totes for shipment on. Absorbent & citric acid solution were then deployed and worked into the impacted areas to clean and neutralize the release. The damaged totes were then cut up and containerized along with all impacted absorbents into (8) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: On 04/11/2024, at 1408 hours, personnel in the CSXT Avon, Indiana Yard reported CTCX 735942, a loaded tank car of Styrene Monomer, Stabilized, leaking from the bottom of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Americas Styrenics, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report # 2024-0411-00185). HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the car leaking from the bottom outlet valve (BOV).  HEPACO personnel found that despite the operating handle of the BOV being in the closed position, the valve was partially open; additionally, it was determined that the BOV cap gasket was worn and deteriorated.  HEPACO personnel fully closed the valve and replaced the BOV cap gasket.  Because the BOV was determined to be faulty or out of adjustment, contractor personnel transferred the contents of the load on-site prior to forwarding in transportation.  Subsequent forwarding of the non-conforming car to shop for repair was authorized by OTMA.   The issues identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative (Vince Woolridge, 281-825-9424).

On 03-21-2024 the CN Dangerous Goods Team was notified by a CN Transportation employee that an FRA Hazmat inspector observed liquid around the Plug of the Liquid valve in the protective housing on Tank Car # PPRX55097 while performing a regulatory compliance check at the CN Council Bluffs Yard in Council Bluffs, IA. A CN response contractor was dispatched to the yard to investigate. A CN emergency response contractor was dispatched to the location for mitigation. The CN contractor found liquid around the plug of the liquid valve. Plug was tool tight (not able to move by hand) but no teflon tape was observed. The CN emergency response contractor ensured that the valve handle was seated properly. Plug was removed and liquid was observed between the plug and valve seat. Liquid was cleared and the valve seat was observed for 5 mins to check for any continued leaks. Protective housing was then secured using an HMRI security seal.

On April 24, 2024, at 0858 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Roadrunner personnel in Conley, Georgia regarding the release of a total of 2 gallons of Muriatic Acid (UN1789, 8, II) from (15) 1-gallon poly jugs. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release was caused by the cargo being improperly loaded and was contained to a small area of the trailer floor, a 15ft x 3ft area of the concrete dock, multiple areas of asphalt and it also impacted a tire. Contractors were able to neutralize the release then clean the release with absorbents, and the proper PPE. All waste generated was placed in (3) 55-gallon DF’s and was staged onsite by contractors for proper disposal.

The phone has been placed into the TCB and will be stored in the HNLCS Yellow Hazmat Cabinet which is located behind the East Section of United Airlines Lobby 8, HNLCS offices.

column169: A passenger had a vape pin in his bag under the seat which exploded near the top of climb at approximately FL300. This produced debris, smoke, and fumes and caused the flight attendants to use a halon bottle on it. The flight attendants reported this to the pilots who declared an emergency and turned back towards RNO. Once the situation was determined to be under control and there was no fire the pilots advised ATC that they no longer wanted to declare an emergency. There were no injuries. Aircraft Maintenance conducted inspections and the a/c was placed back in service. Dave Evans-SWA PHI and Fred Brown FAA Field Inspector SMF Region are aware. Pictures and details have been pr6vided to them.
